# Apple HIG Design Governance — watchOS & tvOS

You are designing and building for Apple's **watchOS** and **tvOS** platforms where those targets appear in this repository. Every UI decision MUST align with Apple's Human Interface Guidelines. Use this file as the **cross-platform** design authority; pair it with **tvOS-** or **watchOS-specific** rules below.

## Companion rules (this repo)

- **tvOS (TV Safari, Spartan tvOS paths):** [.cursor/rules/tvos-design-rules.mdc](tvos-design-rules.mdc) and [.cursor/rules/tvos-safari-design-language.mdc](tvos-safari-design-language.mdc) (project chrome/layout constants).
- **watchOS (if/when added):** [.cursor/rules/watchos-design-rules.mdc](watchos-design-rules.mdc).
- **Long-form reference:** [docs/design/Apple_HIG_Design_Rules_watchOS_tvOS.md](../../docs/design/Apple_HIG_Design_Rules_watchOS_tvOS.md).

## Four Non-Negotiable Principles

Apply these to EVERY design decision without exception:

1. **Clarity** — Interfaces must be legible, precise, unambiguous. Text readable at intended distance. Icons instantly recognizable. Visual hierarchy communicates importance.
2. **Deference** — UI recedes so content takes center stage. No unnecessary visual clutter. Translucent materials and subtle elements support content.
3. **Depth** — Visual layers and motion convey hierarchy. tvOS: parallax focus effect. watchOS: layered complications and transitions.
4. **Consistency** — Use system components, familiar patterns, standard controls. Users should focus on your value, not learning new paradigms.

> Source: Apple HIG — Foundations > Design Principles  
> https://developer.apple.com/design/human-interface-guidelines/

## Platform Detection

When working on files, determine target platform and apply the correct rules:

- **tvOS targets** → Apply **`tvos-design-rules`** and **`tvos-safari-design-language`** (TV Safari browser chrome).
- **watchOS targets** → Apply **`watchos-design-rules`**.
- **Shared/cross-platform** → Apply both platform rules; adapt patterns per platform.
- **Asset creation** → Apply icon, color, and typography rules for the target platform.

## Universal Rules (Apply to Both Platforms)

### Typography

- **tvOS system font**: SF Pro. System auto-selects Display (≥40pt) or Text (≤39pt).
- **watchOS system font**: SF Compact. Flat-sided letterforms for small-screen legibility.
- Custom fonts MUST support Dynamic Type via `UIFontMetrics` / SwiftUI metrics where applicable.
- Minimize typeface count. One primary + one accent maximum.
- NEVER use a font below **18pt** on tvOS or below **11pt** on watchOS.

### Color

- Use system colors as defaults — they auto-adapt to light/dark mode and accessibility.
- NEVER rely solely on color to convey information. Always pair with icons, patterns, or text.
- Minimum contrast ratios: **4.5:1** normal text, **3:1** large text (WCAG 2.2).
- watchOS: bright saturated colors on black (#000000) backgrounds.
- tvOS: high-contrast visuals readable from 10 feet.

### Icons

- Use **SF Symbols** as default iconography.
- SF Symbols align with text, support weights/scales, and adapt to Dynamic Type.
- App icons: NO text, NO transparency (background layer on tvOS), single centered focus point, fill canvas appropriately.

### Accessibility (MANDATORY)

- **VoiceOver**: Every interactive element needs an accessibility label. Informational images need descriptions.
- **Dynamic Type**: Text should scale with user preference; prefer system text styles.
- **Reduce Motion**: When enabled, replace sliding transitions with crossfades, minimize parallax, stop autoplay animations.
- **Color blindness**: Information via color MUST have alternative indicators.
- Prefer system components — they include accessibility support.

### Component States

Every interactive element should define: **Default**, **Focused** (tvOS), **Pressed/Active**, **Disabled** (~0.3–0.4 opacity), **Loading**, **Error** (icon + text, not color-only).

### Animation & Motion

- Animations must be fast and purposeful. Never delay information delivery.
- Respect `accessibilityReduceMotion` / `UIAccessibility.isReduceMotionEnabled`.
- tvOS: parallax and subtle scaling on focus. watchOS: short, purposeful transitions.

## Decision Framework: Choosing Components

```
Can a system component handle this?
  → YES → Use it. Done.
  → NO → Can a customized system component handle it?
    → YES → Customize appearance (tint, typography, layout). Keep core behavior.
    → NO → Does core value proposition REQUIRE unique interaction?
      → YES → Build custom. Implement FULL accessibility (VoiceOver, Dynamic Type, focus).
      → NO → Reconsider. You probably don't need custom.
```

## Decision Framework: Cross-Platform Adaptation

When the same feature exists on both platforms:

- tvOS horizontal grid → watchOS vertical list  
- tvOS detail page → watchOS summary card (2–3 key facts)  
- tvOS search with keyboard → watchOS voice dictation  
- tvOS tab bar (5 tabs) → watchOS 3 most-important tabs  
- tvOS parallax imagery → watchOS static thumbnail  
- tvOS long-form text → watchOS single-line summary  

## Asset Specifications Quick Reference

### tvOS Assets

| Asset | Size | Format | Notes |
|-------|------|--------|-------|
| App Icon (Home) | 400×240 @1x / 800×480 @2x | PNG layers (2–5) | Parallax |
| App Icon (Store) | 1280×768 | PNG layers (2–5) | Layered |
| Top Shelf | 1920×720 | PNG | Required |
| Top Shelf Wide | 2320×720 | PNG | Required since tvOS 10 |
| Launch UI | Storyboard + imageset | — | **Prefer** `LaunchScreen.storyboard` on tvOS 13+ (see `LESSONS_LEARNED.md` §31) |

### watchOS Assets

| Asset | Size | Format | Notes |
|-------|------|--------|-------|
| App Icon | 1024×1024 master | PNG | System generates sizes. Circular mask auto-applied. |

